<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-166-077 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 625 290</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Sources  May 1991 v2 n5 p51(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Sampler of mail-order credit card surcharge policies. (Forum)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lockwood, Russ.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Mail OrderSurveyComputer IndustryCreditEconomics of ComputingPurchases.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Mail-order companies' credit card terms. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>SAMPLER OF MAIL-ORDER CREDIT CARD SURCHARGE POLICIES In the highlycompetitive mail-order arena, some companies are rewriting their credit cardsurcharge policies to lower prices and attract more business.andP;  Lyco ComputerMarketing, for example, recently dropped its 4 percent surcharge for creditcard orders.andM;How can you tell if a mail-order company tags your order for a surcharge,thereby costing you a certain percentage more of the product price?andP;  If an adsays, &quot;No surcharge for credit cards,&quot; the company does not tack on asurcharge.andP;  If you read, &quot;Prices reflect a discount for cash,&quot; chances are afew percentage points will be added to your bill if you pay by credit card.andO;Companies often don't surcharge Visa or MasterCard, but will surchargeAmerican Express, because American Express charges a higher transaction fee.andM;It's a good idea when you call and order to ask about the company's creditcard surcharges in case there are policies you aren't aware of.andP;  Forinstance, Micro World Computers tacks a 3 percent surcharge on RAM chips(margins are too thin to absorb the cost), but not on any other products.andM;Remember, a surcharge is only one part of the product's final price; youshould consider other charges, like shipping and handling, as well as return,service, and support policies.andM;The percentages quoted in the following table give you an idea of thediversity of mail-order credit card surcharge policies.andP;  Abbreviations standfor Visa (V), MasterCard (MC), and American Express (AMEX).andO;</TEXT></DOC>